history.content: EE106AB will mostly cover computer vision in the context of robotics. If you're more interested in robotics side of cv, then yes 106AB should give you decent foundation. For more traditional CV methods, highly suggest taking at least 184, 194-26, 123, and 280 for grad school.

children.subject:
This is suuuuper late, but 106A/B covers almost no CV. 106A covers homography (and uses AR tags) but that's pretty much it. 106B covers none. Many students do do more vision stuff on projects, so it's a great way to practice, and granted a lot of the math is the same, but 194-26 and 280 are really where you want to go.

We're also looking at introducing more vision into 106A, but I'm not sure what's happening with that yet, so I wouldn't count on anything.
